<h3><b>Research experiences and achievements</b></h3>
<p>What I focused on the past few years was the applications of density-functional theory (DFT) calculations to understand how local surface and interface geometries control their functionalities by exploiting theoretical surface characterization approachesŌĆōwhich covers an electronic structure analysis, statistic thermodynamics, theoretical spectroscopy, and microscopy simulations;</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Development and application of theoretical surface characterization</strong></li>
  <li><strong>Oxidation of metal surfaces</strong></li>
  <li><strong>Theoretical aspect of catalysis (water-splitting reaction and CO<sub>2</sub> utilization)</strong></li>
  <li><strong>Polymorphic (polytypic) expression of metal oxide</strong></li>
</ul>

<p>Recently, I am interested in the introduction of machine learning methods to materials science to understand metals or oxides surface properties for the better performances of the heterogeneous catalytic system.</p>

<p>Also, I demonstrated organizing skills, especially writing and presentations skills via publishing the articles as the first- and co-authors in peer-reviewed (highly cited) journals (in the field of physical chemistry, chemical physics, and material science) and participating domestic and international conferences (see <b><a href="/achievements">achievements</a></b>)</p>

